      </div>

      <section>
        <h2>Abstract</h2>
        <p>$ERDOS is a Proof-of-Discovery token that rewards participants for finding twin prime pairs. Unlike traditional Proof-of-Work systems that waste energy on arbitrary hash puzzles, $ERDOS mining produces mathematically significant results — every mined block represents a verified twin prime discovery that contributes to humanity's understanding of prime number distribution.</p>
        <p>Named after Paul Erdős, the most prolific mathematician in history, who offered prizes for solutions to mathematical problems and believed mathematics should be a collaborative, open pursuit.</p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>The Twin Prime Conjecture</h2>
        <p>Twin primes are pairs of primes that differ by 2: (3,5), (5,7), (11,13), (17,19), (29,31)...</p>
        <p>The <strong>Twin Prime Conjecture</strong> states that there are infinitely many twin primes. Despite being one of the oldest unsolved problems in mathematics (first stated by Alphonse de Polignac in 1849), it remains unproven.</p>
        <div class="formula">∃ infinitely many p such that p and p+2 are both prime</div>
        <p>In 2013, Yitang Zhang proved that there are infinitely many prime pairs with gap ≤ 70,000,000. The Polymath project reduced this to 246. The gap between 246 and 2 remains open.</p>
        <p><strong>$ERDOS incentivizes the search.</strong></p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Proof-of-Discovery</h2>
        <p>Traditional mining:</p>
        <div class="formula">SHA-256(nonce + block) &lt; target → waste</div>
        <p>$ERDOS mining:</p>
        <div class="formula">isPrime(p) ∧ isPrime(p+2) ∧ p &gt; currentRecord → reward</div>
        <h3>Reward formula</h3>
        <p>The reward scales with the size of the discovered twin prime pair:</p>
        <div class="formula">reward = log₂(digits(p)) × baseReward</div>
        <p>A 100-digit twin prime earns ~6.6× base reward. A 1000-digit twin prime earns ~10× base reward. A record-breaking twin prime earns a bonus multiplier.</p>
      </section>

